no.motif.types

Interface YieldsJavaCollection<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the contained objects.
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Elements<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    PreparedIterable

    public interface YieldsJavaCollection<T>
    Defines the methods which bridges Motif back to the Java Collection Framework.

    • Method Detail

      • collect

        List<T> collect()
        Get the elements as an immutable List. This is the most common way to obtain a regular implementation of a Java collection. If you need more control on the returned Collection implementation, use collectIn(Collection), e.g. if you need a mutable collection.
        Returns:
        the elements of the iterable as an unmodifiable list.

      • collectIn

        <C extends Collection<T>> C collectIn(C collection)
        Collects the elements in this iterable in the given collection. The caller is responsible for supplying an appropriate collection implementation for what behavior that is expected. Keep in mind that sets does not allow duplicates, and many implementations also does not maintain the order of the elements. The collection must obviously support the add(..) operation. Unless you have particular needs for the resulting collection, consider using the collect() method instead.
        Parameters:
        collection - The collection to add the elements to.
        Returns:
        the given collection is returned.

      • sortedBy

        <P extends Comparable<P>> List<T> sortedBy(Fn<? super T,P> property)

        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • sorted

        List<T> sorted(Comparator<? super T> comparator)
        Get a sorted immutable List of the contents of this iterable.
        Parameters:
        comparator - The comparator to use when sorting the elements. Use Iterate.byOrderingOf(Class) to use the natural ordering of the contained elements.
        Returns:
        the elements of the iterable as a sorted list.

      • groupBy

        <P> Map<P,List<T>> groupBy(Fn<? super T,P> property)
        Get a Map where the keys are derived by applying the given Fn on all elements. Each key points to the list of elements which resolves to the key.
        Parameters:
        property - the function which resolves the key for elements.
        Returns:
        the map.

      • mapBy

        <P> Map<P,T> mapBy(Fn<? super T,P> uniqueProperty)
        Get a Map where all keys are derived by applying the given Fn on all elements. This is a special case of groupBy(Fn) where the Fn will yield a unique key for each element. In the event of multiple elements resolves to the same key, this method will fail with an exception. If this uniqueness cannot be guarantied, consider using groupBy(Fn) instead.
        Parameters:
        uniqueProperty - the function which resolves the unique key for each element
        Returns:
        the map.
